SET 2 â€“ Option Portfolio When Future Stock Prices Are More Volatile
Problem 2 â€“ Changing the Distribution (70/130 vs 80/120)

Consider the portfolio from Solution 1A (K_call=110, K_put=90). Assume:

Risk-free rate is 2%.

Call + put portfolio initial cost is net $7 (as before).

Market is fairly priced so expected return matters.

Case A (original): future stock price is 80 or 120 with equal probability 50% each.

Case B (more volatile): future stock price is 70 or 130 with equal probability 50% each.

A. Compute the expected payoff and expected rate of return on the option portfolio in Case A (80/120).

B. Repeat for Case B (70/130).

C. Compare the expected returns and explain the intuition: how does higher underlying volatility affect the option portfolioâ€™s expected return (and Î²)?

Solution 2

We use the payoff function from Set 1A:

For S_T â‰¤ 90: payoff = S_T âˆ’ 90

90 < S_T < 110: payoff = 0

S_T â‰¥ 110: payoff = S_T âˆ’ 110

Net cost = 7 â†’ expected profit = E[payoff] âˆ’ 7, expected return = profit / 7 (ignoring risk-free rate for simplicity of notation).

A. Case A â€“ S_T âˆˆ {80, 120}

State 1: S_T = 80

80 â‰¤ 90 â†’ payoff = 80 âˆ’ 90 = âˆ’10

State 2: S_T = 120

â‰¥110 â†’ payoff = 120 âˆ’ 110 = 10

Each state 50% probability:

Expected payoff = 0.5(âˆ’10) + 0.5(10) = 0

Expected profit = 0 âˆ’ 7 = âˆ’7

Expected return = âˆ’7 / 7 = âˆ’100%

So under this toy distribution, the portfolio has zero expected payoff but negative expected return relative to its cost; youâ€™re paying $7 for something that breaks even in payoff terms.

(If this were a realistic, fairly priced derivative, the initial cost would be set so expected profit is closer to the risk-free return; here the numbers are stylized.)

B. Case B â€“ S_T âˆˆ {70, 130}

State 1: S_T = 70

70 â‰¤ 90 â†’ payoff = 70 âˆ’ 90 = âˆ’20

State 2: S_T = 130

â‰¥110 â†’ payoff = 130 âˆ’ 110 = 20

Expected payoff:

E[payoff] = 0.5(âˆ’20) + 0.5(20) = 0 (same as before)

But magnitude of good and bad outcomes doubled:

Good state payoff: +20 vs +10

Bad state payoff: âˆ’20 vs âˆ’10

Yet expected payoff is still 0.

Expected profit (again ignoring discounting of initial cost):

E[profit] = 0 âˆ’ 7 = âˆ’7

Expected return = âˆ’7 / 7 = âˆ’100% (same as before).

So numerically we made payoffs more extreme, but kept the distribution symmetric; expected payoff remains 0 and expected return remains âˆ’100% under this stylized setup.

C. Intuition: volatility â†‘ â†’ option value â†‘ (for same price), Î² â†‘

In a realistic setting with market-determined option prices, when underlying volatility rises:

For a given initial option price, expected payoff (in a risk-neutral sense) and option value typically increase (call and put become more valuable; youâ€™re long volatility in this type of portfolio).

If prices adjust so that the option is fairly priced, the initial cost would rise to keep expected return consistent with CAPM; at a fixed old price, higher volatility would mean a higher expected payoff.

Even in this toy symmetric example:

Your payoff is more sensitive to underlying stock moves (âˆ’20/20 instead of âˆ’10/10).

The portfolioâ€™s beta goes up: in boom states you earn more; in bust states you lose more â†’ stronger comovement with the market.

Intuition: your position is more leveraged to underlying risk; with correctly priced options, higher volatility would be reflected in a higher initial cost for the same expected payoff.

So:

Raising dispersion from (80,120) to (70,130) increases risk/Î² and (if price didnâ€™t adjust) would increase expected return because you have more upside in really good states; in a proper market, higher price would offset that so expected return per unit Î² matches CAPM.

SET 3 â€“ Real Options: Coffee CafÃ© with Changed Cashflows

Recall the real options lecture:

Coffee cafÃ© project in Chicago. Two possible â€œpreference typesâ€:

