Problem 3 â€“ Changing the Cashflows

Assume:

Discount rate: r = 10% (one-year horizon for simplicity).

Two possible types for Chicago:

Type B (Berkeley): one-year NPV of cafÃ© = +30K (higher than before).

Type C (Cleveland): one-year NPV of cafÃ© = âˆ’10K (worse than before).

Prior probabilities: P(B) = 60%, P(C) = 40%.

You must decide today whether to build the cafÃ© or not. Alternatively, you can pay a consultant to perfectly reveal type (B vs C), then decide.

A. What is the NPV of investing now without information? (Invest today; pay cost, then receive state-dependent NPV.)

B. What is the value of the project with perfect information (you can invest only if B)?

C. What is the value of information from perfect research?

D. Intuition: how does changing cashflows (higher upside and lower downside vs original 22/12) affect:

NPV without info

NPV with info

Value of information?

Solution 3

We treat the NPV numbers (+30K and âˆ’10K) as already discounted one-year NPVs relative to cost. That is, if you build today, expected payoff in each state (considering all future years and discounting) is:

B: +30K

C: âˆ’10K

If that bothers you, think of them as PV at t=0; weâ€™re not re-discounting further.

A. NPV of investing now (no info)

If you invest now, youâ€™re stuck with B or C:

Expected NPV (no info) = P(B) * NPV_B + P(C) * NPV_C
= 0.6 Ã— 30 + 0.4 Ã— (âˆ’10)
= 18 âˆ’ 4
= +14K

So NPV_no_info = +14K. Good project even without research.

B. Value with perfect information (invest only if B)

With perfect research:

If B (60%): you invest and get +30K.

If C (40%): you do not invest, NPV = 0.

Expected NPV with info:

NPV_with_info = 0.6 Ã— 30 + 0.4 Ã— 0 = 18K

So NPV_with_info = +18K.

C. Value of information

Value of info = NPV_with_info âˆ’ NPV_no_info
= 18K âˆ’ 14K = +4K

So paying anything less than 4K for perfect info would be positive-NPV (ignoring the cost of delay; weâ€™re not discounting time here for simplicity).

D. Intuition: how did changing cashflows change the values?

Compare to the original lecture numbers (where NPV_B and NPV_C were closer, e.g., 22 and 12 or 32.3 and âˆ’27.8 in some versions):

Higher upside in B (+30K instead of +22) and lower (more negative) downside in C (âˆ’10K instead of, say, +12):

In our new numbers, B is more attractive; C is worse than before (negative vs small positive).

This increases the value of being able to avoid C, so it increases the NPV with info relative to no info.

NPV_no_info:

If the prior probability of good state is high (60%) and B is very good (+30), that pulls NPV_no_info up.

If C is negative but relatively modest (âˆ’10), the average NPV remains positive (+14).

NPV_with_info:

With info, you get all of the upside in B and avoid the negative C entirely. Thatâ€™s always going to be at least as big as NPV_no_info, but the gap depends on:

Size of negative NPV in bad states,

Probability of bad states.

Value of information:

Magnitude of VOI depends on both how bad bad states are and how likely they are.

Here, by making C negative (instead of just smaller positive) weâ€™ve made it more important to avoid the wrong project â†’ VOI rises relative to a world where both states had positive NPV but different levels.

Key takeaway:

If you increase the dispersion between â€œgoodâ€ and â€œbadâ€ outcomes (higher upside in B and more negative downside in C), both NPV_no_info and NPV_with_info can change, but:

NPV_with_info always benefits from being able to avoid negative C.

Value of information tends to grow when:

Bad states are truly bad (negative or more negative), and

Those bad states have non-trivial probability.

